It is really a bit surprising that this idea comes up on this list,
since it is really the exact opposite of self organization and self
determination and so on.

I think information theory is important for designing systems of
government. Why doesn't central planning work very well? Because it
will not be able to get enough (and the *right*) information (besides
things like corruption and bureaucracy as well as that it doesn't take
individual preferences into account). The benevolent despot draws this
to an extreme, that despot would have to process *all* relevant
information for his society, something which seems to require at least
SI. But if you have an SI ruler, it is likely that there will be
close-to-SI systems out in society making things even more complex
anyway; the only way to solve it is to have a ruler SI that has an
information processing ability on the same order of the rest of
society - but then you get an *internal* regulation problem for the
ruler, since its own mind is just as complex as the society it tries
to regulate well. Oops :-) Putting the despot into charge of a big and
helpful bureaucracy doesn't solve the problem either, since now the
bureaucracy + despot is equivalent to a SI, with the added problems of
human nature embedded in the system.

